First, let's find the Cartesian product of A and B, denoted as A x B. This is the set of all ordered pairs (a, b) where a ∈ A and b ∈ B.

A x B = {(1, 2), (1, 3), (1, 4), (2, 2), (2, 3), (2, 4), (3, 2), (3, 3), (3, 4)}

Now, let's find the Cartesian product of B and A, denoted as B x A. This is the set of all ordered pairs (b, a) where b ∈ B and a ∈ A.

B x A = {(2, 1), (2, 2), (2, 3), (3, 1), (3, 2), (3, 3), (4, 1), (4, 2), (4, 3)}

Now, we will find the intersection of these two sets, (A x B) ∩ (B x A). This is the set of all ordered pairs that are in both A x B and B x A.

(A x B) ∩ (B x A) = {}

The intersection is an empty set, which means there are no common ordered pairs between A x B and B x A.

This shows that the Cartesian product of two sets is not commutative with respect to intersection because (A x B) ≠ (B x A) and their intersection is an empty set. If the Cartesian product were commutative, then the intersection would have been equal to either A x B or B x A, which is not the case here.
